  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "Hi,\r\n\r\nI have run into an usability issue in which Helm was instantiating a dependent chart that I thought I had already updated.\r\n\r\nLet's say I have a chart with two dependencies:\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\n$ cat requirements.yaml \r\n\r\ndependencies:\r\n  - name: mariadb\r\n    version: 0.5.x\r\n    repository: https://kubernetes-charts.storage.googleapis.com/\r\n  - name: redis\r\n    version: 0.4.x\r\n    repository: https://kubernetes-charts.storage.googleapis.com/\r\n```\r\n\r\nResolving:\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\n$ cat requirements.lock \r\ndependencies:\r\n- name: mariadb\r\n  repository: https://kubernetes-charts.storage.googleapis.com/\r\n  version: 0.5.5\r\n- name: redis\r\n  repository: https://kubernetes-charts.storage.googleapis.com/\r\n  version: 0.4.2\r\ndigest: sha256:a568b70bc50c9d83d39d8414ded20943124988afa6faf5e591b581858d002335\r\ngenerated: 2017-01-24T16:57:02.467414576-08:00\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen I update my dependencies by doing `helm dependency update` and getting a new version of the MariaDB chart.\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n$ git status\r\nOn branch master\r\nChanges not staged for commit:\r\n  (use \"git add <file>...\" to update what will be committed)\r\n  (use \"git checkout -- <file>...\" to discard changes in working directory)\r\n\r\n        modified:   requirements.lock\r\n\r\nUntracked files:\r\n  (use \"git add <file>...\" to include in what will be committed)\r\n\r\n        charts/mariadb-0.5.6.tgz\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe issue is that the updater has not removed my previous version of the MariaDB chart and so it gets instantiated. \r\n\r\n```bash\r\nls charts/\r\nmariadb-0.5.5.tgz  mariadb-0.5.6.tgz  redis-0.4.2.tgz\r\n```\r\n\r\nI am wondering if we should make the `helm dependency update` command delete previous/outdated charts in the same way `bundler` does in a vendorized directory.\r\n\r\nI know that this is not a problem if I do not \"vendor/cache\" the charts under the `charts` directory but I am doing it this way so I reduce networking dependencies in our CI/CD pipelines.  \r\n\r\nRegards,\r\nMiguel",
